on of police leaders as not simply the result of individual experiences and attitudes, but of the social, institutional and historical processes of policing and the cultures that exist within it; - Points towards future directions and a reimagining of leadership in the police. Accessible and stimulating, this is an essential text for policing students and valuable reading for current leaders and those interested in policing, criminology and leadership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aLeadership. 0aPolice administration. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aO’Neill, Megan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilvestri, Marisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSilvestri, Marisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTong, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311119671840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447349655423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447349655/original  a978-3-11-119671-8  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles